{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17539215","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17539215"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:38:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:38:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16482"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16482","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16482"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.06,0.06,0.04,0.66]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9173"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66967"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9173","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9173"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16482"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52421"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"3663"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4984"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21779"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37290"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43945"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66967","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66967"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a five-day history of bloody diarrhoea and cramping abdominal pain. She returned from a three-week backpacking trip to India two weeks ago. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She works as a primary school teacher.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 118/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Her abdomen is soft with mild tenderness in the left lower quadrant. Stool microscopy reveals trophozoites containing ingested red blood cells.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Albendazole","Trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole","Ciprofloxacin","Oral rehydration solution only","Metronidazole followed by paromomycin"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with bloody diarrhoea after travel to an endemic area, and stool microscopy reveals trophozoites containing red blood cells, which is pathognomonic for \u003Cem\u003EEntamoeba histolytica\u003C/em\u003E infection. The presence of ingested red blood cells within trophozoites distinguishes pathogenic \u003Cem\u003EE. histolytica\u003C/em\u003E from non-pathogenic species.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetronidazole followed by paromomycin\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate treatment. Metronidazole is effective against invasive disease, while paromomycin is required as a luminal agent to eliminate colonisation and prevent transmission. This two-step approach is necessary because metronidazole alone does not eradicate intestinal colonisation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECiprofloxacin\u003C/strong\u003E is commonly used for bacterial causes of dysentery such as \u003Cem\u003EShigella\u003C/em\u003E or \u003Cem\u003ECampylobacter\u003C/em\u003E but is not effective against amoebic infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlbendazole\u003C/strong\u003E is an antiparasitic medication primarily used for helminth infections such as hookworm or roundworm. It is not effective against protozoan infections like \u003Cem\u003EE. histolytica\u003C/em\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for bacterial infections such as traveller\u0027s diarrhoea caused by enterotoxigenic \u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E, but it is not effective against amoebic dysentery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral rehydration solution\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be insufficient treatment. While maintaining hydration is important, specific antimicrobial therapy is required to treat the infection and prevent complications such as liver abscess.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Entamoeba histolytica infection typically presents with bloody diarrhoea and abdominal pain after travel to endemic areas.","Metronidazole is the first-line treatment for symptomatic amoebic dysentery.","A luminal agent (paromomycin) is required after metronidazole to eliminate colonisation."],"references":["Kantor M, Abrantes A, Estevez A, et al. Entamoeba Histolytica: Updates in Clinical Manifestation, Pathogenesis, and Vaccine Development. Can J Gastroenterol Hepatol. 2018 Dec 2;2018:4601420."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52421"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16482"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52421","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52421"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-03T09:09:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-03T09:10:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9173"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66967"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","